    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                
                <p>I am very happy to hear of y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> safe arrival <del>&amp;</del>in <placeName ref="pl0699">town</placeName> 
                    &amp; hope to have many pleasant walks with you next month. I flatter myself that we shall meet about the 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 
                    &amp; so reserve all chat till that time. Moses <add place="above"><persName ref="pe0014">Griffith</persName></add><note type="editorial">The name 'Griffith'
                    is added in pencil, not in Thomas Pennant's hand.</note> &amp; I have contracted for another two years &amp; I shall bring him with me in order to 
                    be instructed, that he may do justice to our welch antiquities. <gap unit="letters" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>You &amp; I will instantly 
                    walk to <persName ref="pe0216">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Morris</persName> &amp; see what he has. as to y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> kind offer 
                    about books at present I have only to beg you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> look out for these two:<note type="editorial">The 'two' mentioned may have 
                        been named on the 'note' to which Pennant refers later in this letter. They could possibly be identified with the '2 last vols of Kalm' named in the 
                        final paragraph.</note> they are sometimes to be met with single; but more frequently, bound with <persName ref="pe0804">de Bry's</persName> other works 
                    which are too expensive. be so good as to take care of the note. if you go by <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> White</persName>'s bookseller 
                    in <placeName ref="pl1012">Fleetstreet</placeName> please to leave with him the inclosed carrier's receit.</p>
                
                <p><persName ref="pe0078">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Forster</persName> may be heard of at <persName ref="pe0805">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Lownds</persName> 
                    next door to <persName ref="pe0026">Whites</persName>; He will deliver you the 2 last vols of <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0614">Kalm</title></bibl>. 
                    <persName ref="pe0234">Bel</persName> &amp; <persName ref="pe0065">Davy</persName> join in complim<hi rend="superscript">ts</hi> &amp; I am Dear Sir</p>
                  
                <closer><salute>your faithfull &amp;<lb/>
                    most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                </salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName></signed>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> March 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1771.</dateline></closer>
                
                
         
                
            </div>
            <div><p><stamp>PENNY POST PAID W WE; 7 O'CLOCK T</stamp></p></div>
            <div>      
                <p><address><addrLine>To<lb/><persName ref="pe0803">John Lloyd esq<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</persName> N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 1.<lb/> 
                    <lb/><placeName ref="pl1344">Garden Court in the Temple</placeName>.
                    </addrLine></address></p>
            </div>
